 for bestpractices and # 500 Server Error Page

## Overview
Create a robust, user-friendly 500 Server Error Page for LifeOps that gracefully handles server-side failures, provides clear guidance to users, and facilitates immediate support contact. The page should communicate the error clearly, offer retry options, present self-service guidance, and provide channels to reach support. It must adhere to strict runtime safety rules for all code generation (null checks, safe defaults, etc.) and align with the LifeOps design system and accessibility requirements.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A specialized error page that surfaces a 500 Internal Server Error state to users within LifeOps. It conveys that something went wrong on the server, reassures the user, and provides actionable next steps.

Goals:
- Clearly communicate that a server error occurred.
- Provide an actionable retry option and immediate contact/support pathway.
- Maintain design consistency with LifeOps UI (dark UI, high contrast typography, subtle depth).
- Ensure accessibility: sufficient color contrast, keyboard navigability, screen-reader friendly text, and descriptive aria labels.
- Minimal disruption to user workflow: offer clear next steps and potential causes at a glance.

Connected features:
- No external APIs required for core rendering; the page should gracefully handle absence of network/data dependencies.
- Should integrate with LifeOps error logging/audit framework if available (e.g., emit an error run artifact, log error context for traceability).

UI elements and visual guidance:
- Large, prominent error heading (e.g., "Something went wrong on our side").
- Clear explanation beneath the heading.
- Retry button to reattempt the failed operation (with disabled/enabled states based on context).
- Contact Support section with a link or button to open a support modal or navigate to a contact page.
- Quick guidance/tips: possible causes, suggested actions (refresh, come back later), and expected timelines if known.
- Visual priority: error message first, then guidance, then contact options.
- Layout: responsive, centered content on larger canvases, with appropriate padding and card-like surface that matches LifeOps aesthetics.
- Visual style: dark UI framing, subtle elevation, careful use of the accent color (#FF3B30) for error emphasis, and supportive neutrals for guidance text.
- Microcopy: approachable, concise, and human-friendly tone.

API integrations:
- None required for the page rendering. If your stack uses an error-tracking service, optionally surface a lightweight, non-blocking integration point to log the error with context (e.g., error id, timestamp, user id if available).

## Components to Build
- 500ServerErrorPage (main page)
  - Header: breadcrumb or small page label aligned with LifeOps top chrome
  - Main Error Card: elevated dark card containing the error message, status, and icon
  - RetryAction: primary action button that triggers a retry callback or navigates back to a known safe route
  - GuidanceList: list of self-help steps or potential causes
  - ContactSupportSection: call-to-action to contact support (opens modal or navigates)
  - Toast/AlertArea (optional): ephemeral messages for retry status or failure details
- SupportModal (optional)
  - Pre-filled context (error id, page, timestamp)
  - Fields for users to add a short description
  - Submit action to route to support or ticket system
- ErrorContextHook (optional)
  - Custom hook to capture error info, generate an errorId, and provide a ready-to-display context payload

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- UI Components
  - 500ServerErrorPage
    - Props: onRetry?: () => void; errorId?: string; retryDisabled?: boolean
    - Render: prominent heading, explanatory copy, retry button, contact support CTA, quick guidance
    - Accessibility: role="status" region for error content, aria-live regions if dynamic updates occur
  - RetryActionButton
    - Text: "Retry" (or localized equivalent)
    - States: enabled/disabled; shows a spinner when retry is in progress
  - GuidanceList
    - List items with small icons and concise bullet guidance
  - ContactSupportSection
    - CTA: "Contact Support" button/link
    - Optional inline phone/email hints if policy allows
  - SupportModal (optional)
    - Form fields: Description, Attachments (optional), Priority
    - Validation: required description, length limits
  - ErrorIcon
    - Visual cue (e.g., a stylized server/warning glyph) with accessible alt text
- Data Handling and Safety
  - Do not rely on data that could be null; use data ?? [] patterns when mapping lists
  - Guard all array operations:
    - (items ?? []).map(...)
    - Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : []
  - Use proper state initialization:
    - const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false)
    - const [errorId, setErrorId] = useState<string | null>(null)
  - If backend provides error context via props or context, validate shapes with Array.isArray checks and optional chaining
- Design System Alignment
  - Implement per the Visual Style and UI Guidelines provided
  - Use the specified color palette with emphasis red for errors
  - Typography: Inter or system sans, 12–14px body, 16–20px headings as appropriate
  - Spacing: 8px baseline grid; card padding 16–20px
  - Card design: dark elevated card, subtle border, top-highlight gradient
- Responsiveness and Accessibility
  - Desktop: centered content with generous margins
  - Mobile: content stacks, touch targets >= 44px, accessible focus outlines
  - ARIA: aria-labels for buttons, roles for status messages, aria-describedby for descriptive text
- Performance
  - Lightweight rendering; avoid unnecessary re-renders
  - Debounce or guard any retry logic to prevent rapid-fire calls

### Backend
- Not required for the core 500 page rendering
- If you choose to implement an optional support-ticket trigger, provide a minimal API surface:
  - POST /api/support/tickets
    - Body: { subject, description, errorId, page, timestamp }
    - Response: { success: boolean, ticketId?: string }
- For error logging (optional): emit an event to the existing LifeOps error-logging system with fields:
  - errorId, message, page, userId (if available), timestamp, stack (sanitized)

### Integration
- Page routing: ensure this page is accessible via a route like /500 or a unified error route within the app
- Global error boundary integration (optional): if an error boundary triggers, redirect or render this 500 page with captured context
- The Retry action should reuse existing retry/backoff utilities if applicable (or call a provided retry handler)
- Support modal integration should reuse existing modal/dialog patterns and styling

## User Experience Flow
1. User encounters a 500 error on a LifeOps page (e.g., a dashboard section or module screen).
2. The app renders the 500 Server Error Page with a descriptive error header and concise explanation.
3. User sees recommended actions in GuidanceList (e.g., refresh the page, check back later, contact support if the issue persists).
4. User can click the Retry button.
   - If retry is in progress, show a spinner and disable repeated clicks.
   - If retry succeeds, navigate back to the previous page or restore prior state.
   - If retry fails, keep the error page visible with an updated message or logs.
5. If user cannot recover, they click Contact Support to open SupportModal or navigate to the support page.
6. If the user submits a support ticket, the system acknowledges receipt and shows a confirmation toast or message.
7. The page optionally surfaces an errorId for reference to support personnel and the user can copy it.

## Technical Specifications
- Data Models:
  - ErrorContext (optional)
    - errorId: string
    - message: string
    - page: string
    - timestamp: string
    - userId?: string
    - stack?: string
- API Endpoints:
  - GET /api/status or /500 to render page with optional context
  - POST /api/support/tickets (optional)
- Security:
  - Ensure that any support contact path routes to authenticated context if required by policy
  - Do not leak sensitive server-side details in user-facing content; sanitize error messages
- Validation:
  - All user-provided input in SupportModal should be validated on the client and server (if implemented)
  - Destructure props with defaults; validate errorId presence; ensure retryDisabled toggles safely

## Acceptance Criteria
- The 500 Server Error Page renders correctly on a 500 state with:
  - Accurate, accessible heading and explanation
  - A functional Retry button with loading state and proper disabling while retry is in progress
  - A clearly visible Contact Support CTA that opens a modal or navigates to support
  - Guidance items that are rendered safely with null-safe mapping
- No runtime crashes due to null/undefined values in arrays or objects
  - All array operations guarded: (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray checks
  - All API data uses: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
- State initialization follows best practices:
  - useState([]) for array-type state
  - Defaults to appropriate types
- Visual/Design coherence with LifeOps design system and color palette
- Accessibility requirements met: aria-labels, roles, focus outlines, and readable contrast
- If SupportModal is used, it validates input and submits to the backend correctly (if implemented)

## UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
- Maintain the dark UI aesthetic with the specified color palette
- Use high-contrast typography and clear visual hierarchy
- Provide subtle depth through shadows and gradients
- Ensure consistent spacing, typography, and component behavior with LifeOps
- Ensure consistent error handling language: empathetic, actionable, and non-technical where possible

---

## Visual Style

(Consistent with the provided Visual Style section in PROJECT CONTEXT)

- Color Palette
  - Primary background: #0B0B0C
  - Secondary surface: #151718
  - Tertiary surface / borders: #1F1F20
  - Text: #FFFFFF
  - Secondary text: #9DA3A6
  - Subtle text: #56595B
  - Accent: #FF3B30
  - Neutral highlight: #CFCFCF
  - Soft highlight: #E6E7E8
  - Supporting accents: teal #00C2A8, amber #FFB020, purple #8B5CF6
  - Borders: rgba(255,255,255,0.03)
  - Gradients: #111213 → #1A1A1B

- Typography & Layout
  - Font: Inter (or SF Pro Display / Roboto fallback)
  - Heading weights: 600–700, 20–28px
  - Card titles: 14–16px, 500–600 weight
  - Body: 12–14px, 400 weight
  - Microcopy: 11–12px, 300–400 weight
  - Spacing: 8px baseline grid; card paddings 16–20px
  - Layout: responsive centering, accessible focus outlines

- Key Design Elements
  - Error Card: elevated, rounded corners, top highlight gradient
  - Buttons: Primary (filled), Secondary (outlined)
  - Support interactions: clear affordances, accessible descriptions
  - Minimalist data viz not required for this page, but keep overall aesthetic consistent

